# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hdr-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Graphics processor company Nvidia summarizes the motivation for HDRR in three points: bright things can be really bright, dark things can be really dark, and details can be seen in both.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The use of high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI) in computer graphics was introduced by Greg Ward in 1985 with his open-source Radiance rendering and *lighting simulation* software which created the first file format to retain a high-dynamic-range image.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI languished for more than a decade, held back by limited computing power, storage, and capture methods.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Not until recently has the technology to put HDRI into practical use been developed.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1990, Eihachiro Nakame and associates presented a lighting model for driving simulators that highlighted the need for high-dynamic-range processing in realistic simulations.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1995, Greg Spencer presented *Physically-based glow visual effects for digital images* at SIGGRAPH, providing a quantitative model for flare and blooming in the human eye.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1997, Paul Debevec presented *Recovering high dynamic range radiance maps from photographs* at SIGGRAPH, and the following year presented *Rendering synthetic objects into real scenes*.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These two papers laid the framework for creating HDR *light probes* of a location, and then using this probe to light a rendered scene.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI and HDRL (high-dynamic-range image-based lighting) have, ever since, been used in many situations in 3D scenes in which inserting a 3D object into a real environment requires the light probe data to provide realistic lighting solutions.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In gaming applications, *Riven: The Sequel to Myst* in 1997 used an HDRI postprocessing shader directly based on Spencer's paper.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] After E3 2003, Valve released a demo movie of their Source engine rendering a cityscape in a high dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The term was not commonly used again until E3 2004, where it gained much more attention when Epic Games showcased Unreal Engine 3 and Valve announced *Half-Life 2: Lost Coast* in 2005, coupled with open-source engines such as OGRE 3D and open-source games like *Nexuiz*.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] By the 2010s, HDR displays first became available.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] With higher contrast ratios, HDRR can reduce or eliminate tone mapping, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the primary advantages of HDR rendering is that details in a scene with a large contrast ratio are preserved.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Without HDRR, areas that are too dark are clipped to black and areas that are too bright are clipped to white.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These are represented by the hardware as a floating point value of 0.0 and 1.0 for pure black and pure white, respectively.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another aspect of HDR rendering is the addition of perceptual cues which increase apparent brightness.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR rendering also affects how light is preserved in optical phenomena such as reflections and refractions, as well as transparent materials such as glass.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In LDR rendering, very bright light sources in a scene (such as the sun) are capped at 1.0.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] When this light is reflected the result must then be less than or equal to 1.0.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, in HDR rendering, very bright light sources can exceed the 1.0 brightness to simulate their actual values.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This allows reflections off surfaces to maintain realistic brightness for bright light sources.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The human eye can perceive scenes with a very high dynamic contrast ratio, around 1,000,000:1.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Adaptation is achieved in part through adjustments of the iris and slow chemical changes, which take some time (e.g. the delay in being able to see when switching from bright lighting to pitch darkness).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At any given time, the eye's static range is smaller, around 10,000:1.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, this is still higher than the static range of most display technology.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although many manufacturers claim very high numbers, plasma displays, liquid-crystal displays, and CRT displays can deliver only a fraction of the contrast ratio found in the real world, and these are usually measured under ideal conditions.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The simultaneous contrast of real content under normal viewing conditions is significantly lower.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Some increase in dynamic range in LCD monitors can be achieved by automatically reducing the backlight for dark scenes.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, LG calls this technology "Digital Fine Contrast"; Samsung describes it as "dynamic contrast ratio".
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another technique is to have an array of brighter and darker LED backlights, for example with systems developed by BrightSide Technologies.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] OLED displays have better dynamic range capabilities than LCDs, similar to plasma but with lower power consumption.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 709 defines the color space for HDTV, and Rec.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 2020 defines a larger but still incomplete color space for ultra-high-definition television.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Since the 2010s, OLED and other HDR display technologies have reduced or eliminated the need for tone mapping HDRR to standard dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Light blooming is the result of scattering in the human lens, which human brain interprets as a bright spot in a scene.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, a bright light in the background will appear to bleed over onto objects in the foreground.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This can be used to create an illusion to make the bright spot appear to be brighter than it really is.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Flare is the diffraction of light in the human lens, resulting in "rays" of light emanating from small light sources, and can also result in some chromatic effects.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is most visible on point light sources because of their small visual angle.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typical display devices cannot display light as bright as the Sun, and ambient room lighting prevents them from displaying true black.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Thus, HDR rendering systems have to map the full dynamic range of what the eye would see in the rendered situation onto the capabilities of the device.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This tone mapping is done relative to what the virtual scene camera sees, combined with several full screen effects, e.g. to simulate dust in the air which is lit by direct sunlight in a dark cavern, or the scattering in the eye.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping and blooming shaders can be used together to help simulate these effects.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping, in the context of graphics rendering, is a technique used to map colors from high dynamic range (in which lighting calculations are performed) to a lower dynamic range that matches the capabilities of the desired display device.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typically, the mapping is non-linear – it preserves enough range for dark colors and gradually limits the dynamic range for bright colors.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This technique often produces visually appealing images with good overall detail and contrast.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Various tone mapping operators exist, ranging from simple real-time methods used in computer games to more sophisticated techniques that attempt to imitate the perceptual response of the human visual system.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR displays with higher dynamic range capabilities can reduce or eliminate the tone mapping required after HDRR, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Currently HDRR has been prevalent in games, primarily for PCs but was previously prevalent in Microsoft's Xbox 360and Sony's PlayStation 3.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It has also been simulated on the PlayStation 2, GameCube, Xbox and Amiga systems.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Sproing Interactive Media had announced that their Athena game engine for the Wii will support HDRR, which added the Wii to the list of systems that support it.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In desktop publishing and gaming, color values are often processed several times over.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As this includes multiplication and division (which can accumulate rounding errors), it is useful to have the extended accuracy and range of 16-bit integer or 16-bit floating point formats.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This is useful irrespective of the aforementioned limitations in some hardware.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Complex shader effects began their days with the release of Shader Model 1.0 with DirectX 8.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 1.0 illuminated 3D worlds with what is called standard lighting.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Lighting calculations were integer based, which didn't offer as much accuracy because the real world is not confined to whole numbers.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On December 24, 2002, Microsoft released a new version of DirectX.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] DirectX 9.0 introduced Shader Model 2.0, which offered one of the necessary components to enable rendering of high-dynamic-range images: lighting precision was not limited to just 8-bits.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although 8-bits was the minimum in applications, programmers could choose up to a maximum of 24 bits for lighting precision.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, all calculations were still integer-based.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the first graphics cards to support DirectX 9.0 natively was ATI's Radeon 9700, though the effect wasn't programmed into games for years afterwards.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 23, 2003, Microsoft updated DirectX to DirectX 9.0b, which enabled the Pixel Shader 2.x (Extended) profile for ATI's Radeon X series and NVIDIA's GeForce FX series of graphics processing units.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 9, 2004, Microsoft updated DirectX once more to DirectX 9.0c.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This also exposed the Shader Model 3.0 profile for High-Level Shader Language (HLSL).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 3.0's lighting precision has a minimum of 32 bits as opposed to 2.0's 8-bit minimum.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Also all lighting-precision calculations are now floating-point based.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] NVIDIA states that contrast ratios using Shader Model 3.0 can be as high as 65535:1 using 32-bit lighting precision.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At first, HDRR was only possible on video cards capable of Shader-Model-3.0 effects, but software developers soon added compatibility for Shader Model 2.0.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As a side note, when referred to as Shader Model 3.0 HDR, HDRR is really done by FP16 blending.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending is not part of Shader Model 3.0, but is supported mostly by cards also capable of Shader Model 3.0 (exceptions include the GeForce 6200 series).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending can be used as a faster way to render HDR in video games.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 is a feature of DirectX 10, which was released with Windows Vista.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 allows 128-bit HDR rendering, as opposed to 64-bit HDR in Shader Model 3.0 (although this is theoretically possible under Shader Model 3.0).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 5.0 is a feature of DirectX 11.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It allows 6:1 compression of HDR textures without noticeable loss, which is prevalent in previous versions of DirectX HDR texture compression techniques.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is possible to develop HDRR through GLSL shader starting from OpenGL 1.4 onwards.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The term is often used in discussing the dynamic ranges of images, videos, audio, or radio.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] It may also apply to the means of recording, processing, and reproducing such signals including analog and digitized signals.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In this context, the term *high dynamic range* means there is a large amount of variation in light levels within a scene or an image.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The *dynamic range* refers to the range of luminosity between the brightest area and the darkest area of that scene or image.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Modern films have often been shot with cameras featuring a higher dynamic range, and legacy films can be post-converted even if manual intervention will be needed for some frames (as when black-and-white films are converted to color).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Also, special effects, especially those that mix real and synthetic footage, require both HDR shooting and rendering.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] HDR video is also needed in applications that demand high accuracy for capturing temporal aspects of changes in the scene.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] This is important in monitoring of some industrial processes such as welding, in predictive driver assistance systems in automotive industry, in surveillance video systems, and other applications.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In photography and videography, a technique, commonly named *high dynamic range* (*HDR*) allows the dynamic range of photos and videos to be captured beyond the native capability of the camera.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] It consists of capturing multiple frames of the same scene but with different exposures and then combining them into one, resulting in an image with a dynamic range higher than the individually captured frames.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Some of the sensors on modern phones and cameras may even combine the two images on-chip.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] This also allows a wider dynamic range being directly available to the user for display or processing without in-pixel compression.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Some cameras designed for use in security applications can capture HDR videos by automatically providing two or more images for each frame, with changing exposure.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] For example, a sensor for 30fps video will give out 60fps with the odd frames at a short exposure time and the even frames at a longer exposure time.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Modern CMOS image sensors can often capture high dynamic range images from a single exposure.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] This reduces the need to use the multi-exposure HDR capture technique.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] High dynamic range images are used in extreme dynamic range applications like welding or automotive work.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In security cameras the term used instead of HDR is "wide dynamic range".
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Because of the nonlinearity of some sensors image artifacts can be common.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] High-dynamic-range rendering (HDRR) is the real-time rendering and display of virtual environments using a dynamic range of 65,535:1 or higher (used in computer, gaming, and entertainment technology).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] HDRR does not require a HDR display and originally used tone mapping to display the rendering on a standard dynamic range display.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The technologies used to store, transmit, display and print images have limited dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] When captured or created images have a higher dynamic range, they must be tone mapped in order to reduce that dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] High-dynamic-range formats for image and video files are able to store more dynamic range than traditional 8-bit gamma formats.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] High dynamic range (HDR) is also the common name of a technology allowing to transmit high dynamic range videos and images to compatible displays.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] That technology also improves other aspects of transmitted images, such as color gamut.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] On January 4, 2016, the Ultra HD Alliance announced their certification requirements for an HDR display.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The HDR display must have either a peak brightness of over 1000 cd/m2 and a black level less than 0.05 cd/m2 (a contrast ratio of at least 20,000:1) or a peak brightness of over 540 cd/m2 and a black level less than 0.0005 cd/m2 (a contrast ratio of at least 1,080,000:1).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The two options allow for different types of HDR displays such as LCD and OLED.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Some options to use HDR transfer functions that better match the human visual system other than a conventional gamma curve include the HLG and perceptual quantizer (PQ).
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] HLG and PQ require a bit depth of 10-bits per sample.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The dynamic range of a display refers to range of luminosity the display can reproduce, from the black level to its peak brightness.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The contrast of a display refers to the ratio between the luminance of the brightest white and the darkest black that a monitor can produce.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Multiple technologies allowed to increase the dynamic range of displays.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In May 2003, BrightSide Technologies demonstrated the first HDR display at the Display Week Symposium of the Society for Information Display.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] The display used an array of individually-controlled LEDs behind a conventional LCD panel in a configuration known as "local dimming".
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] BrightSide later introduced a variety of related display and video technologies enabling visualization of HDR content.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In April 2007, BrightSide Technologies was acquired by Dolby Laboratories.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In the 1970s and 1980s, Steve Mann invented the Generation-1 and Generation-2 "Digital Eye Glass" as a vision aid to help people see better with some versions being built into welding helmets for HDR vision.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In Audio, the term *high dynamic range* means there is a lot of variation in the levels of the sound.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Here, the *dynamic range* refers to the range between the highest volume and lowest volume of the sound.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] XDR (audio) is used to provide higher-quality audio when using microphone sound systems or recording onto cassette tapes.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] HDR Audio is a dynamic mixing technique used in EA Digital Illusions CE Frostbite Engine to allow relatively louder sounds to drown out softer sounds.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Dynamic range compression is a set of techniques used in audio recording and communication to put high-dynamic-range material through channels or media of lower dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Optionally, dynamic range expansion is used to restore the original high dynamic range on playback.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In radio, high dynamic range is important especially when there are potentially interfering signals.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] Measures such as spurious-free dynamic range are used to quantify the dynamic range of various system components such as frequency synthesizers.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] HDR concepts are important in both conventional and software-defined radio design.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] In many fields, instruments need to have a very high dynamic range.
[src:hdr-imaging/high-dynamic-range] For example, in seismology, HDR accelerometers are needed, as in the ICEARRAY instruments.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] It is notable for supporting multiple channels of potentially different pixel sizes, including 32-bit unsigned integer, 32-bit and 16-bit floating point values, as well as various compression techniques which include lossless and lossy compression algorithms.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] It also has arbitrary channels and encodes multiple points of view such as left- and right-camera images.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] A full technical introduction of the format is available on the OpenEXR website.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR, or EXR for short, is a deep raster format developed by ILM and broadly used in the computer-graphics industry, both visual effects and animation.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR's multi-resolution and arbitrary channel format makes it appealing for compositing, as it alleviates several painful elements of the process.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] Since it can store arbitrary channels—specular, diffuse, alpha, RGB, normals, and various other types—in one file, it takes away the need to store this information in separate files.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] The multi-channel concept also reduces the necessity to "bake" in the aforementioned data to the final image.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] If a compositor is not happy with the current level of specularity, they can adjust that specific channel.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR's API makes tools development a relative ease for developers.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] Since there are almost never two identical production pipelines, custom tools always need to be developed to address problems (e.g. image-manipulation issue).
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR's library allows quick and easy access to the image's attributes such as tiles and channels.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] The OpenEXR library is developed in C++ and is available in source format as well as compiled format for Microsoft Windows, macOS and Linux.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] Python bindings for the library are also available for version 2.x.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR was created by ILM in 1999 and released to the public in 2003 along with an open source software library.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] It soon received wide adoption by software used in computer graphics, particularly for film and television production.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] The format has been updated several times, adding support for tiles, mipmaps, new compression methods, and other features.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] In 2007, OpenEXR was honored with an Academy Award for Technical Achievement.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] OpenEXR 2.0 was released in April 2013, extending the format with support for deep image buffers and multiple images embedded in a single file.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] Version 2.2, released August 2014, added the lossy DWA compression format.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] There are three general types of lossless compression built into OpenEXR, with two different methods of Zip compressing.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] For most images without a lot of grain, the two Zip compression methods seem to work best, while the PIZ compression algorithm is better suited to grainy images.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] deflate compression applied to blocks of 16 scanlines at time.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] This tends to be the most effective style of compression to use with rendered images that do not have film grain applied.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] This form of compression is quite effective when dealing with grainy images, and will often surpass any of the other options under grainy conditions.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] converts 32-bit floats to 24 bits then uses deflate compression.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] It is lossless for half and 32-bit integer data and slightly lossy for 32-bit float data.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] This form of compression is lossy for half data and stores 32-bit data uncompressed.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] It maintains a fixed compression size of either 2.28:1 or 4.57:1 and is designed for realtime playback.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] B44 compresses uniformly regardless of image content.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] An extension to B44 where areas of flat color are further compressed, such as alpha channels.
[src:hdr-imaging/openexr] Same as DWAA, but compresses blocks of 256 scanlines.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] The **perceptual quantizer** (**PQ**), published by SMPTE as **SMPTE ST 2084,** is a transfer function that allows for HDR display by replacing the gamma curve used in SDR.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] Its 0–1 value range represents luminance levels from 0 to 10,000 cd/m2 (nits).
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] It was developed by Dolby and standardized in 2014 by SMPTE and also in 2016 by ITU in Rec.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] ITU specifies the use of PQ or HLG as transfer functions for HDR-TV.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is the basis of HDR video formats (such as Dolby Vision, HDR10 and HDR10+) and is also used for HDR still picture formats.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is not backward compatible with the BT.1886 EOTF (i.e. the gamma curve of SDR), while HLG is compatible.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is a non-linear transfer function based on the human visual perception of banding and is able to produce no visible banding in 12 bits.
[src:hdr-imaging/perceptual-quantizer] A power function (used as EOTFs in standard dynamic range applications) extended to 10000 cd/m2 would have required 15 bits.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] It defines various aspects of HDR-TV such as display resolution (HDTV and UHDTV), frame rate, chroma subsampling, bit depth, color space, color primaries, white point, and transfer function.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] It was posted on the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) website on July 4, 2016.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 uses a wide color gamut (WCG) which is the same as Rec.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 defines two sets of HDR transfer functions which are perceptual quantization (PQ) and hybrid log-gamma (HLG).
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 with a nominal peak luminance of 1,000 cd/m2 and a system gamma value that can be adjusted depending on background luminance.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] For a reference viewing environment the peak luminance of display should be 1000 cd/m2 or more for small area highlights and the black level should be 0.005 cd/m2 or less.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] The surround light should be 5 cd/m2 and be neutral grey at standard illuminant D65.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 uses the same color primaries as Rec.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] These resolutions have an aspect ratio of 16:9 and use square pixels.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] Only progressive scan frame rates are allowed.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 specifies a bit depth of either 10-bits per sample or 12-bits per sample, with either narrow range or full range color values.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] A future-use and intermediate linear RGB format using IEEE 16 bit floating point representation for each channel is also specified.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] For narrow range color, 10-bit per sample signals use video levels where the black level is defined as 64, achromatic gray level as 512 and the nominal peak as 940 in RGB, Y, and I encoding and 960 in Cb/Cr, and Ct/Cp component encoding.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 12-bit per sample signals define 256 as the black level, 2048 as the gray level and the nominal peak is 3760 in RGB, Y, and I component encoding and 3840 in Cb/Cr, and Ct/Cp component encoding.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] Narrow range signals may extend below black or above peak white (super-black and super-white respectively), but must always be clipped to the signal range of 4-1019 for 10-bit signals or 16-4079 for 12-bit signals.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 specifies the use of RGB, YCbCr, and ICtCp.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] ICtCp provides an improved color representation that is designed for high dynamic range (HDR) and wide color gamut signals (WCG).
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 allows for RGB, YCbCr, and ICtCp signal formats with 4:4:4, 4:2:2, and 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] 2100 specifies that if a luma (Y') signal is made it uses the same matrix coefficients as Rec.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] BT.2020 the chroma sample location that was in use was center left.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] But in H.265 (2018–02) top-left chroma siting was mandated for BT.2020-2 and BT.2100-1, that must be described in VUI (video usability information) as such.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] First value of VUI should be 2 for top-left chroma and 0 for center left.
[src:hdr-imaging/rec-2100] Blu-ray also uses top-left chroma for HDR, including for Dolby Vision.
